[[File:Saxton's Frontispiece.jpg|thumb|Frontispiece to Saxton's ''Atlas of the Counties of England and Wales'']]
'''Christopher Saxton''' (c. 1540 – c. 1610) was an English [[cartographer]] who produced the first county maps of England and Wales.

==Life and family==
Saxton was probably born in Sowood, [[Ossett]] in the parish of [[Dewsbury]], in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire]] in either 1542 or 1544. His family subsequently moved to the hamlet of [[Dunningley]] near [[Tingley]] in the parish of [[Woodkirk]] where the Saxton name is recorded in 1567.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=1|ps=}} It is speculated that Saxton may have attended the predecessor school to [[Queen Elizabeth Grammar School, Wakefield]] and also speculated that he was a student at [[Cambridge University]] but neither is corroborated.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=5|ps=}} It is most likely that [[John Rudd (cartographer)|John Rudd]], the vicar of Dewsbury and [[Thornhill, West Yorkshire|Thornhill]], a keen [[Cartography|cartographer]] passed his skills to Saxton.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=6|ps=}}

Saxton married and had three children. Robert, born in 1585 was his father's assistant in 1601 and drew a map of Snapethorpe in Wakefield when it was surveyed by his father. Robert was commissioned to survey [[Sandal Magna]] in 1607.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=3|ps=}} Christopher Saxton died in either 1610 or 1611.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=2|ps=}}

==Career==
[[File:Saxton's map of Southamptonshire.jpg|thumb|A map of "Southamptonshire" (modern day [[Hampshire]]) from the ''Atlas of the Counties of England and Wales'']]
[[File:Saxton’s Proof Map of Wales.jpg|thumb|Saxton’s unpublished Proof Map of Wales, 1580]]
Map making became increasingly common in the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]] made possible by advances in surveying technology and printing from engraved copper plates. Accurate mapping of the whole country became increasingly important. [[William Cecil, 1st Baron Burghley|Lord Burghley]] was instrumental in ensuring that a court official, [[Thomas Seckford]] of [[Woodbridge, Suffolk]], financed the commission.<ref name ="BL">{{citation |title=Saxton’s map of Northumbria|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/mapsviews/saxtonmap/ |publisher=British Library |accessdate=14 May  2014}}</ref> In 1574 Saxton began the survey of England.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=7|ps=}} In consideration of the expenses involved, Queen Elizabeth granted him a lease on lands at Grigstone Manor in Suffolk. The Welsh survey began in 1577.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=11|ps=}} Surveying the country was a significant undertaking but the first plates were engraved by 1574 and in 1578 the survey was complete.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=9|ps=}} As the task was finished in a short timespan is possible that Saxton used some of John Rudd's earlier work.<ref name ="BL"/> Individual county sheets were issued before the completed survey was issued as an atlas in 1579. The proofs were presented to Lord Burghley who compiled them into an atlas of his own.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=9|ps=}}

The maps were produced in the ''Atlas of the Counties of England and Wales'' published in 1579, the first atlas of any country. It contained 35 maps, each bearing the arms of [[Elizabeth I]] and Thomas Seckford, Saxton's patron. The maps show hills and mountains but do not provide precise information as to their location or altitude. A variety of symbols show buildings and settlements.{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=9|ps=}} All the maps are dated except for Northumberland. Five counties, Cornwall, Essex, Hertfordshire, The Suffolk and Norfolk maps show the division into [[Hundred (county division)|hundreds]].{{sfn|Evans|Lawrence|1979|p=10|ps=}} The atlas was a commercial success, prompting other cartographers including [[John Speed]], John Norton, and [[Michael Drayton]] to attempt similar enterprises, adding to and adapting Saxton's work.{{sfn|Ferrington|2002|p=107|ps=}}

The maps drawn by Saxton were engraved by [[Augustine Ryther]], [[Remigius Hogenberg]], William Hole, William Kip, Leonard Terwoort of Antwerp, Nicholas Reynold of London, Cornelius Hogius, and Francis Scatter. The engravers were of Dutch or Flemish origin.<ref name ="BL"/> There is no evidence on the maps that Saxton engraved them himself, but according to one account, he engraved those of the Welsh counties and Herefordshire. Saxton obtained a license to sell the maps for a term of ten years.<ref>{{cite DNB|wstitle=Saxton, Christopher}}</ref>

[[John Dee]], warden of the [[Manchester Cathedral|Manchester's collegiate church]] employed Saxton to survey Manchester's parish boundaries in 1596 but no copy has survived.<ref>{{citation |title=101 Treasures of Chetham's: Material associated with John Dee (1527-1608) |url=http://www.chethams.org.uk/treasures/treasures_dee.html |publisher=Chetham's |accessdate=16 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140416230255/http://www.chethams.org.uk/treasures/treasures_dee.html |archivedate=16 April 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[Chetham's Library]] in Manchester has a copy of the atlas,<ref>{{citation|title=101 Treasures of Chetham's|url=http://www.chethams.org.uk/treasures/treasures_saxton.html|publisher=Chetham's|accessdate=31 October 2012|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120831024033/http://www.chethams.org.uk/treasures/treasures_saxton.html|archivedate=31 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as does the [[Folger Shakespeare Library]] in Washington, D.C.{{sfn|Ferrington|2002|p=107|ps=}}

