[[File:North Sea map-en.png|thumb|240px|Map of the North Sea, showing the location of the Fladen Ground.]]
'''Fladen Ground''' is an area in the [[Scottish sector of the North Sea|Scottish sector]] of the [[North Sea]], between Scotland and Norway, about {{convert|100|mi}} northeast of [[Aberdeen]].<ref name="Witbaard">{{cite journal|last=Witbaard|first=Rob|title=Growth Variations in Arctica Islanda L. (Mollusca): a reflection of hydrography-related food supply|journal=ICES Journal of Marine Science|year=1996|url=http://icesjms.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/reprint/53/6/981.pdf|doi=10.1006/jmsc.1996.0122}}</ref> The [[Fair Isle]] current and East [[Shetland|Shetland Islands]] Atlantic inflow form an eddy, creating a  weak, [[anti-clockwise]] rotating vortex that is evidenced in the surface form of the seabed.<ref name="Witbaard"/><ref name="Ithaca1">Athena Field Development, p 61</ref> Due to stratification of the water column in the summer months, seasonal variation of the temperature in deep water is low ({{convert|5.7|-|8|C|disp=comma|sigfig=2}}).<ref name="Witbaard"/> Average water depth is in the range of {{convert|100|-|150|m|ft fathom|abbr=on}}, and the mostly muddy sea floor has been created by incoming sediments from the surrounding sea areas.<ref name="Witbaard"/><ref name="Ithaca2">Athena Field Development, p 60</ref> The dominant benthic animals are [[polychaete]]s and [[shellfish]] and other [[seafood]]s are common.<ref name="Witbaard"/>

Fladen Ground is rich in [[oil]] and [[natural gas]] and offers good [[fishing]].<ref Name="Ithaca5">Athena Field Development, p 7</ref><ref name="Ithaca3">Athena Field Development, p 68</ref> Scottish vessels catch low-fat fish species, and [[lobster|Norway lobster]]. Danish and English vessels catch [[Northern prawn]].<ref name="Ithaca4">Athena Field Development, p 84</ref>
